{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01BXkLL2Nd1eyh4XBEciC3ZN","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `svelte-kit sync` (which is part of `pnpm check`) is failing because SvelteKit doesn't like test files with `+` prefix inside the routes directory. The error is:\n```\nFiles prefixed with + are reserved (saw src/routes/api/photos/+server.test.ts)\n```\n\nThis is a problem - `svelte-kit sync` (which runs before `svelte-check`) fails because SvelteKit treats all files starting with `+` in the routes directory as route files, and it only accepts specific names like `+server.ts`, `+page.ts`, etc. \n\nThe issue is that `+server.test.ts` doesn't match any valid route pattern, so SvelteKit rejects it. I should move the test files out of the routes directory entirely—either to a separate `src/__tests__/` or `src/tests/` directory, or rename them to drop the `+` prefix. Moving them to a dedicated test directory seems cleanest since it keeps them logically organized while avoiding the routes directory restrictions.\n\nActually, I realize renaming them to `server.test.ts` (without the `+`) might work better—SvelteKit only processes files starting with `+`, so test files without that prefix should be safely ignored even if they're in the routes directory. This keeps the tests co-located with their corresponding route files. The issue is that SvelteKit reserves all `+`-prefixed filenames, so `+server.test.ts` triggers an error even though it's not a recognized route pattern. I need to rename these files to `server.test.ts` in both route directories, and since the Vitest pattern already matches that naming convention, the tests should be picked up automatically.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2609,"cache_read_input_tokens":66714,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2